This is by far the best Indian/ Nepalese food I have ever experienced! I have written only a hand full of Yelp Reviews in my life and this by far is worth a 5 star review, which speaks volumes!!! The atmosphere is absolutely charming, authentic and blissful. I smile the entire time I'm here listening to the culturally tuned music and the sweetness of the entire staff. I am in Love with this place and I want to shout out loud, tell my neighbor and sing the praises of Little Nepal restaurant!!! My new favorite by FAR!!

I wanted to like this food based on other yelp reviews, so I ordered for delivery, but did not like a thing except delivery, which was quick. The white rice was steamed and bland (no other choice) and the Khasiko Masio Masu looked like soupy ground-up bits of something (was to be chicken) with nary a mushroom in sight, and only a few peas. It was frankly unappetizing. The flavor was nice at best. I decided I just didn't like garlic naan, so will pass on a review of that. The best? The vegetable soup, and the food arrived quickly, but sadly, I won't try this place again.

Amazing little place with great salmon curry dish. Very friendly staff. I would definitely go again when In town and try other dishes.

I've never had Himalayan/Nepalese food. So, I was a little nervous bringing my wife, and 75-year-old mother here. Nepal is northeast of India and thought that my mom would burn her mouth on everything she ate and blame me for pooping fire. I was wrong. She was very happy. The short: we were not disappointed with any of the dishes I was served here. Everything was delicious. The restaurant has a very cozy feel to it. It is well lit and well decorated without feeling overly done. The servers were nice. Dishes: chicken momo (potsticker-like dumplings), lamb chhoila (bbq-ed meat, even my lamb hating wife loved), alu tama bodi (think lentil soup with bamboo shoots), kukhura ra mula (marinated boneless chicken served with bell peppers and onion on a sizzing platter), and the machhako mitho takari (salmon on a sizzling platter). Drinks: Himalayan milk (chai w/ milk), sudha dahi (sweet yogurt) Ate way too much. Chhoila and sudha dahi is a must.

Excellent service everyone very friendly, excellent food and prices. Street/meter parking or free on side streets, but very busy neighborhood Parking can be difficult. Excellent place

Went here a few nights ago with family and was treated to a truly delicious dinner. We started off with the Himalayan Momo - really tasty dumplings especially when dipped in the sauce along with Samosas and the Mismas Pakauda - a spinach dish with onion and spices. All served as a great prelude to our main courses of Poleko Khasi (lamb) and Poleko Kukhura (chicken) - that was served beautifully. Lamb especially is a tricky dish to prepare as many times the gamey taste is too obvious but this was not the case at all here. The service was timely, polite and courteous and the ambience was perfect. Photos of Nepalese culture and locations line the walls and might even inspire some to climb Everest at some point. I am looking forward to returning here for another meal in the future.

About the Business

Business owner information

Nepal N.

Manager

Traditional Nepalese food using the finest locally-sourced ingredients from the Bay Area. This food is from Northern India and Tibet. The Nepalese cuisine tends to reflect the unique geographical position of Nepal, which is wedged between India to the south and Tibet to the north. Their contrasting influences create a complex nepali cultural synthesis, which manifests itself also in the lively interaction of the remarkably diverse nepali ethnic groups and religious traditions. Likewise its cuisine is influenced by both the dishes from the indian planes and the exotic specialties of the high Himalayas. But it reflects also the diversity and the spirit of Nepal in the variety and the balance of its gastronomical offerings (somewhat fiery at times, but with various degrees of milder components).…

    11/10/2014Previous review

    Yasssss I've finally gotten to try Nepalese/Himalayan food! Been wanting to for a while.
    This place is in Bernal Heights - parking isn't bad. Interior is cozy and clean.

    Got the set meal for $49 which was ALOT of food and got to try their signature dishes. A bit pricey but the quality and quantity of the food made it worth it.

    Pork momo's: This was literally like Chinese dumplings but the dough was thicker. Nothing special to me as a Chinese person but a decent dumpling!

    Lamb samosa: The samosa was HUUUUGE! I usually don't care for samosas because they are dry and barely contain any filling, but this one - the batter was light and just the right thickness to hold all the filling in. Super flavorful and moist inside. Nom nom nom probably my favorite of the night:

    Chicken chhoila. Kinda looks like tandoori (cubed chicken on a sizzling plate. Again, it looked dry but it was so moist- definitely the moistest chicken tandoori ever. HOW U DO THAT. I have no idea what flavors they used but it was different and not in a bad way!

    Poleko kukhura (not sure what this was - some kinda vegetable curry!?) It came with the curry, rice, roti, and then some other chutney's/curries...... it was pretty average, nothing special but the plate sure was huge! I think I only ate half of everything.

    Overall, recommend! Bring a friend here if you want to try something different.
